"In the 2017 motion picture of The Shape of Water, the United States government captures a new species, an amphibian man, Eliza, a mute woman who works at the facility that houses him, falls in love with him and rescues him, her employer"
"a man named Strickland, investigates this disappearance until eventually discovering Eliza intends to release the amphibian man into the sea"
"Over the course of the film, we see various ways in which social systems oppressed minorities or people with less political power"
"Ableism in the form of how Eliza is treated due to her disability, racism, of course, sexism"
"Well, it's the 1950s"
"So what do you think? The Amphibian Man is not a direct allegory for any particular oppressed people, The way say lesser films clumsily utilize allegory instead, The Amphibian Man is more of a grander symbol for the concept of the other director"
Guillermo del Toro explained it himself
The monster is a cipher
It's a symbol
"It's an embodiment of more than anything else, Other Ness"
I needed to talk about acceptance and love in a very urgent way
"I feel it as an immigrant that has been received by this country, but I still feel there is a sort of demonization of the other"
very present
